		title: "Cognitive Robotics",
		slot: 5,
		description: "<p>Crucial aspects of human cognition are our abilities to selectively focus attention torelevant objects among the vast amount of stimuli in our immediate environment andto control our actions towards these objects in such a way we eventually reach ourgoals. Clearly, object perception, action planning and goals need to align in orderto successfully interact with the world. This is the case for humans as well as forartificial cognitive systems, such as robots.In my research I focus on the theoretical underpinnings and computationalmechanisms that underlie this alignment. As it appears, the interaction betweenperception and action planning is greatly determined by automatic processes (i.e.,out of our cognitive control). However, the subjective interpretation of the task/goalcontext can bias these processes in such a way that our behavior is a result of thedynamic interplay between controlled and automatic influences. Indeed, we do feel incontrol of our behavior, most of the time…In this talk I will present a neurally inspired, computational architecture(‘HiTEC’) that enables the modeling of a variety of perception-action related,behavioral experiments. It is my conviction that computational models can contributeto a better understanding of the mechanisms underlying cognition and that theseinsights can further advance our ability to successfully devise intelligent and useful robots.</p>",
		speaker: {
